<p>
Code 128 is a linear (1D) barcode type that is designed to efficiently encode alphanumeric data. It was developed in 1981 by Ted Williams of Laserlight Corporation as a way to store both text and numeric information while maintaining a high data density. One of the key features of Code 128 is its ability to compress numerical data, which allows for more efficient encoding. In addition, it includes checksum controls and byte parity verification to ensure the validity of the data. Overall, Code 128 is a reliable and efficient barcode type that is widely used in a variety of applications, such as shipping, logistics, manufacturing, healthcare, and more. The specification for Code 128 is published in standard ISO/IEC 15417:2007.<br>For more information about this barcode type, see our information article:
